audience on healthy holiday eating yesterday.

Sports nutritionexpcrt offers her
recipe for healthy holiday eating

ISTEPHANIE FERNANDES
The Pitt News

According to Leslie Bonci, it’s possi-
blc to enjoy holiday foods without ending
up looking like Santa Claus.

Bonci is the director of sports nutri-
tion at UPMC Presbyterian, and suggests
that eating smaller, more frequent meals,
eating tasty, enjoyable foods and taking
time out to relax with a cup of tea are
simple methods of enjoying holiday
treats while still monitoring a healthy
diet. ’

There are tricks to using low-fat
foods and desirable dishes —— in small
portions -—— to pamper the palate, Bonci
said.

She said soy protein can be substitut-
ed for proteins from red meat, chicken or
ﬁsh, and that soy products help protect
against breast, prostate and other malig-
nant cancers. But, she said, soy pills
aren’t the way to go. Instead, she sug-
gestcd consuming about three low-fat
dairy foods ——ranging from low-fat milk
to yogurt or low-fat cheese —— in order to
consume the requisite amount of soy.

According to Bonci, there’s room for
alcohol in a healthy diet -—— but only in
small portions. One ounce of alcohol per
day for women has been found to reduce
the risk of breast cancer. Alcohol is a
blood thinner and decreases the chance of

stroke as long as it is taken into the body
in safe proportions. It also lowers choles-
terol and reduces the risk of heart disease.

Fruits and vegetables serve as great
antioxidants and are vital in keeping

body cells healthy, she said. The deeper A

the color, the more nutritious the‘ food.
Bonci said that deep orangc- and yellow-

colored foods are good for the eyes. Red, V

purple or blue fruit—1ikc berries and
plums are good for the memory.

Tomatoes help reduce the risk of prostate 1

cancer. White or green vegetables such
as onions, garlic, chives, and leeks con-
tain ally sulﬁdes that may decrease the
risk of tumors.

Tea, she said, is very ‘beneﬁcial not
only therapeutically, but also because it
reduces the risk of heart disease and cav-
ities. Bonci recommends drinking at least
two cups of brewed tea per day.

And although herbal tea docsn’t offer_

the same beneﬁts, it’s‘ helpful to healthy
relaxation.

. Bonci offered “a few ﬁnal thoughts, A

aimed at maintaining good health during

the holiday season. “Make eating a prior— v I

ity, not the afterthought,” she said.

She advised those in attendance to’
eat when they are hungry, not categoriz-
ing foods as either “good” or “bad.” And
above all, she instructed healthful hope-

fuls to make changes in eating habits A

gradually.

