EDITORIAL

Not for profit: State shouldn’t
privatize Philly school district

If you are reading this, you’re doing 

better than 87 percent of high school juniors
in the Philadelphia public school system,
according to Gov. Mark Schweiker.

The Washington Post reports that 57
percent of students in the system fail the
state’s basic math and reading tests and 50
percent drop out Schweiker said that only
13 percent of high school juniors can read a
newspaper with adequate comprehension.

Obviously, something needs to be done
to rescue the city’s schools. But the com-
monwealth’s plan to take them over and
place operations in the hands of Edison Inc.,

. a for-proﬁt school management  is not"

the answer.

Under this new plan, the governor will

ﬁre the district’s top 55 administrators and
turn their jobs over to Edison managers.
The company would directly run 60 of the
worst schools —— in conjunction with
church groups, universities, business own-
ers and local politicians.

While a manager may be able to make
the schools ftuiction better ﬁnancially, a
manager’s ability to meet the bottom line
says nothing about how he or she could
improve the quality of a student’s educa-
tion. Parents are already worried that
Edison would cut extracurricular activities,
ﬁne arts and other academic programs if
that meant the difference in making a prof-

IL - - "
Although it is important for a school to
maintain ﬁnancial health, its ﬁrst priority
should be educating its students. That is not
the ﬁrst priority of a for-proﬁt corporation.

This plan also includes $150 million
from the state and city. The state should
instead give the current administration the
chance to improve its services with this sig-
niﬁcant amount of extra money before it
guts the system. As teachers’ union spokes-
woman Barbara Goodman said in the
Washington Post, “If we are going to throw
money around, let’s throw it at programs
that work.”

The state also needs to take a closer
look at why the students are failing and why
so many leave school._ Simply changing the
school’s administration will not do anything
to alleviate deeper problems that affect stu-
dents’ performance, such as poverty and
neighborhood violence.

Hartford, Conn., Minneapolis and
many other cities have already abandoned
failed privatization experiments. Only 28
percent of respondents in a poll by a com-
munity activist group said they supported
the plan, and even Mayor John Street
opposes it.

Yet those pushing the privatization plan
persist. Perhaps they need some = more
schooling themselves.

